entry.sense:
with various uses and significations, like the English verb to be. 
    As substantive verb. 
      Of persons and things, to be, exist: Ac 17:28, Jo 1:1, 8:58, 17:5, al; ὁ ὢν καὶ ὁ ἦν (for past ptcp.), Re 1:4, 8, 4:8, 11:17, 16:5 (v. Swete, Ap., 5; M, Pr., 228); τὰ (μὴ) ὄντα, Ro 4:17, I Co 1:28.  
      Of times, events, etc., to be, happen, take place: Mt 24:3, Mk 14:2, 15:42, Lk 21:23, Jo 4:6, 23, 5:10, al.  
      to be present, be in a place, have come: Mt 2:13, 15, Mk 1:45, 5:21, 15:40, Lk 1:80, 5:29, Jo 7:30, al.; seq. εἰς, Mk 2:1; seq.  ἐκ, (ἐξ), Mt 1:20, 21:25, Mk 11:30, Jo 3:31, al.  
      Impers.,  ἔστι, ἦν, etc.; 
        there is (Fr. il y a), was, etc.: Mt 16:28, Lk 16:19, Jo 3:1, 5:2, Ro 3:10, al.; c. dat. (of the possessor; Bl., §37, 3), Mt 16:22, Lk 1:7, Jo 18.10, Ro 9:2, al.;  ἔστιν ὅς, ὅστις (chiefly in pl), Mt 16:28, 19:2, Mk 9:1, al.; 
        c. inf., = ἔξεστιν (q.v.), it is possible: He 9:5, I Co 11:20, RV (but v. ICC, in l.). 
    As copula uniting subject and predicate. 
      Expressing simply identity or equivalence: Mt 5:13, 14:15, Lk 1:18, 19, Jo 1:1, 4:19, Re 3:9, al. mult. 
      Explicative, as in parable, figure, type, etc.: Mt 13:19, I Co 9:2, 10:4, 11:25, Ga 4:24, Re 17:15, al.; ταῦτ’ ἔστιν, Mt 27:46, Mk 7:2, Ro 7:18 al.; ὅ ἐστιν, Mk 3:17, Col 1:24, He 7:2, al.; akin to this is the sacramental usage: Mt 26:26-28, Mk 14:22, 24, Lk 22:19, I Co 11:24 (v. ICC on Mk, I Co, ll. c.; DB, iii, 148 f.).  
      C. gen.: qual., etc., Mk 5:42, Lk 3:23, I Co 14:33, He 12:11, al.; part., I Ti 1:20, II Ti 1:15; poss., Mt 5:3, 10, Mk 12:7, Lk 4:7; of service or partisanship, Ro 8:9, I Co 1:12, II Co 10:7, II Ti 2:19.  
      C. dat. (BL, §37, 3): Ac 1:8, 9:15, Ro 4:12, I Co 1:18, 2:14, Re 21:7, al.  
      C. ptcp., as a periphrasis for the simple verb (Bl., §62, 1, 2; M, Pr., 225 ff.); 
